---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Our Approach"
  description="Australian Home Collective takes a practical before-you-buy approach to home storage and organisation guides, focusing on measurements, fit, mistakes and household use."
>
  <header class="page-intro">
    <div class="narrow">
      <p class="eyebrow">Before you buy</p>
      <h1>Our Approach</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        Australian Home Collective takes a before-you-buy approach to home guides.
      </p>
    </div>
  </header>

  <section class="content narrow">
    <p>
      Many home websites start with products. We usually start with the problem.
    </p>
    <p>
      That means asking:
    </p>
    <ul class="feature-list">
      <li>What is actually causing the clutter?</li>
      <li>What space needs to be measured?</li>
      <li>What will block the product from fitting?</li>
      <li>Will it suit a rental?</li>
      <li>Will it be easy to clean?</li>
      <li>Will it make daily use easier?</li>
      <li>Does the household need to buy anything at all?</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Why we start before the purchase</h2>
    <p>
      A storage product can be well made and still be wrong for a particular home.
    </p>
    <p>
      It may be too tall for the shelf, too deep for the cupboard, too awkward for a rental,
      too hard to clean, too heavy to move, or too complicated to maintain.
    </p>
    <p>
      The right buying decision often depends on the space, not just the product.
    </p>

    <h2>Practical over perfect</h2>
    <p>
      Australian Home Collective is not about perfect display homes.
    </p>
    <p>
      The guides are written for real households with limited bench space, awkward drawers,
      rental limits, busy routines, mismatched containers, deep cupboards and everyday clutter.
    </p>
    <p>
      A useful system should be easy to use and easy to reset.
    </p>

    <h2>When not buying is the better answer</h2>
    <p>
      Not every household problem needs another product. Sometimes the better first step is to:
    </p>
    <ul class="feature-list">
      <li>remove duplicates</li>
      <li>clear expired pantry items</li>
      <li>match lids to containers</li>
      <li>move rarely used appliances</li>
      <li>group items by use</li>
      <li>measure the space properly</li>
      <li>choose a simpler system</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Buying storage before sorting the problem can make a home feel more crowded, not less.
    </p>

    <h2>How to use the guides</h2>
    <p>
      Use Australian Home Collective guides before shopping. Start with the relevant room
      or problem, check the measurements, read the common mistakes, and decide whether a
      product type actually suits your home.
    </p>
    <p>
      The aim is not to buy more. The aim is to buy more carefully.
    </p>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
